4  levels.   
  
8.3.
More  info:  This  question  has  a  variety  of  possible  answers.  The  key  is  for  a   
researcher  to  be  as  detailed  as  is  necessary  given  the  specifics  of  their  design. 
Be  careful  to  determine  if  every  parameter  has  been  specified  in  the  description   
of  the  study  design.  There  may  be  some  overlap  between  this  question  and  the   
following  questions.  That  is  OK,  as  long  as  sufficient  detail  is  given  in  one  of  the   
areas  to  provide  all  of  the  requested  information.  For  example,  if  the  study  design   
describes  a  complete  factorial,  2  X  3  design  and  the  treatments  and  levels  are   
specified  previously,  you  do  not  have  to  repeat  that  information.  
 
 
 
STUDY  DESIGN: 
 
 
The  study  design  features  two  primary  experimental  manipulations:  a  within-participants   
manipulation  of  trial-type  in  a  task-switching  paradigm  ( task-switch  vs.  task-repeat )  and  a   
within-participants  manipulation  of  reward  amount  for  correct  answers  ( larger  vs.  smaller )  in  the   
task-switching  paradigm.  As  in  the  original  study,  the  former  manipulation  will  involve  either   
switching  or  repeating  one  of  two  tasks:  magnitude  estimation  (greater  or  less  than  5)  versus   
“even  or  odd”  judgments  of  the  numeral  displayed  on  a  standard  playing  card.   The  latter   
manipulation  will  involve  receiving  either  $.05  or  $.01  for  each  correct  answer.   The  reward   
amount  condition  will  remain  consistent  over  a  full  set  of  trials  in  the  task-switching  paradigm.  
 
There  will  also  be  between-participants  manipulations  of  the  order  of  the  two  reward  conditions   
( larger-firs t  vs.  smaller-first )  and  the  stimulus  set  ( order1  vs.  order2 )  assigned  to  each  reward   
condition.   Thus,  the  overall  design  is  a  2(trial  type)  x  2(reward  amount)  x  2(reward  order)  x   
2(stimulus  set)  factorial,  with  repeated-measures  on  the  first  two  factors.  The  focal  analysis  for   
SCORE  additionally  includes  a  measured  covariate  (Need  for  cognition)  and  the  analysis  for   
Hypothesis  1  requires  a  second  measured  covariate  (anticipated  intrinsic  motivation  for  the   
task).  
 
______  
 
 
 
 

9.
Randomization  
 
9.1.
If  you  are  doing  a  randomized  study,  how  will  you  randomize,  and  at  what  level?  
 
9.2.
Example:  We  will  use  block  randomization,  where  each  participant  will  be   
randomly  assigned  to  one  of  the  four  equally  sized,  predetermined  blocks.  The   
random  number  list  used  to  create  these  four  blocks  will  be  created  using  the   
web  applications  available  at  http://random.org.   
  
9.3.
More  info:  Typical  randomization  techniques  include:  simple,  block,  stratified,  and   
adaptive  covariate  randomization.  If  randomization  is  required  for  the  study,  the   
method  should  be  specified  here,  not  simply  the  source  of  random  numbers.  
 
 
 
RANDOMIZATION:  
 
As  consistent  with  the  raw  data  files  from  the  original  study,  for  the  Task-Switching  task,  within   
each  block  of  14  trials,  seven  cards  marked  with  hearts  and  seven  cards  marked  with  spades   
will  appear.   Each  suit  will  include  cards  numbered  from  2  –  9,  excluding  5.   The  presentation  of   
each  of  these  stimuli  will  be  block-randomized.   This  will  be  done  by  assigning  a  stimulus   
number  from  1-14  to  each  card  and  then  generating  random  sequences  of  these  integers  using   
random.org.   Ten  different  block-randomized  sequences  will  be  generated  for  the  10  total  blocks   
of  the  first  set  of  trials  in  the  task-switching  paradigm,  and  participants  will  then  all  complete  the   
full  sequence  of  140  trials  in  the  same  order.   After  evaluating  the  number  of  repeat  versus   
switch  trials  this  creates  (see  below),  manual  adjustments  will  be  made  so  that  the  number  of   
trial  types  for  each  stimulus  type  as  are  equivalent  as  possible  (although  one  of  these   
categories  will  have  one  fewer  trial  because  the  first  trial  of  the  sequence  can  be  neither  a   
switch  or  a  repeat  from  the  trial  before  it).  This  whole  procedure  will  then  be  repeated  for  the   
second  set  of  trials  in  the  task-switching  paradigm.  
 
 
 
The  between-participants  order  manipulation  for  the  within-participants  reward  condition  will  be   
fully  counter-balanced  with  the  two  different  trial  sequences.   The  online  software  used  to   
present  stimulus  materials  will  randomly  assign  participants  to  one  of  four  Order  (large-reward   
first  vs.  small-reward  first)  x  Trial  Sequence  (1  vs.  2)  conditions  with  the  constraint  that  an  equal   
number  of  participants  be  assigned  to  each  condition.   
  
 
 
 
 
As  consistent  with  the  raw  data  files  from  the  original  study,  for  the  Stroop-task  measure  of   
executive  function  required  to  test  Hypothesis  1,  within  each  block  of  12  trials,  each  color  word   
(“red”,  “blue”,  “green”)  will  appear  four  times  each.   In  three  of  these  appearances,  the  word  will   
appear  in  the  congruent  color.   In  the  remaining  instance,  the  word  will  appear  in  an  incongruent   
color  (“red”  in  a  blue  font,  “green”  in  a  red  font,  and  “blue”  in  a  green  font).   The  presentation   
order  of  each  of  these  stimuli  will  be  block-randomized  by  the  experimental  program  for  10  total   
blocks  for  each  individual  participant.  
 
 
 
