12.
Data  collection  procedures  (required)  
 
12.1.
Please  describe  the  process  by  which  you  will  collect  your  data.  If  you  are  using   
human  subjects,  this  should  include  the  population  from  which  you  obtain   
subjects,  recruitment  efforts,  payment  for  participation,  how  subjects  will  be   
selected  for  eligibility  from  the  initial  pool  (e.g.  inclusion  and  exclusion  rules),  and   
your  study  timeline.  For  studies  that  donÍt  include  human  subjects,  include   
information  about  how  you  will  collect  samples,  duration  of  data  gathering  efforts,   
source  or  location  of  samples,  or  batch  numbers  you  will  use.   
  
12.2.
Example :  Participants  will  be  recruited  through  advertisements  at  local  pastry   
shops.  Participants  will  be  paid  $10  for  agreeing  to  participate  (raised  to  $30  if   
our  sample  size  is  not  reached  within  15  days  of  beginning  recruitment).   
Participants  must  be  at  least  18  years  old  and  be  able  to  eat  the  ingredients  of   
the  pastries.  
 
12.3.
More  information :  The  answer  to  this  question  requires  a  specific  set  of   
instructions  so  that  another  person  could  repeat  the  data  collection  procedures   
and  recreate  the  study  population.  Alternatively,  if  the  study  population  would  be   
unable  to  be  reproduced  because  it  relies  on  a  specific  set  of  circumstances   
unlikely  to  be  recreated  (e.g.,  a  community  of  people  from  a  specific  time  and   
location),  the  criteria  and  methods  for  creating  the  group  and  the  rationale  for  this   
unique  set  of  subjects  should  be  clear.  
 
 
 
DATA  COLLECTION  PROCEDURES:  
 
Participants  will  be  recruited  from  the  online  subject  pool  managed  by  the  website  prolific.co  and   
complete  all  tasks  and  materials  online  using  Qualtrics  and  the  Inquisit  Web  software   
( https://www.millisecond.com/products/inquisit6/weboverview.aspx )  .  Although  the  original   
Sandra  &  Otto  (2018)  does  not  report  any  demographics  for  their  sample,  participants  for  this   
study  were  recruited  from  a  university  subject  pool  and  community  in  Canada.   Participants  for   
the  current  study  will  therefore  be  limited  to  individuals  born  and  living  in  North  America  who   
report  English  as  their  first  language.   In  addition,  because  the  original  sample  was  likely  mostly   
comprised  of  university  students,  only  participants  between  the  ages  of  18  and  40  will  be   
recruited.  Participants  will  first  read  the  consent  form  and  indicate  informed  consent.   They  will   
then  report  their  age  and  gender,  and  complete  the  Need  for  Cognition  and  BIS/BAS  individual   
difference  measures  (see  Qualtrics_survey.docx).  One  attention-check  item  that  instructs   
participants  to  select  a  particular  response  will  be  embedded  in  the  Need  for  Cognition   
questionnaire  (question  #16;  see  Qualtrics_survey.docx)  and  one  will  be  embedded  in  the   
BIS/BAS  questionnaire  (question  #7;  see  Qualtrics_survey.docx).   These  items  will  be  used  to   
exclude  participants  who  are  not  carefully  reading  these  questionnaires  (see  section  22  below).  
 
 
 
 
 
Participants  will  next  complete  a  computerized  Stroop  task  run  through  Inquisit  Web   
(stroop_Sanders.iqx),  which  will  require  them  to  identify,  as  quickly  and  as  accurately  as  possible,   
which  one  of  three  colors  the  word  on  the  screen  is  presented:  red,  green,  or  blue,  by  pressing  one   
of  three  keys  ( j ,  k ,  and  l  respectively)  using  their  dominant  hand  while  ignoring  the  meaning  of  the   

word.  Before  starting  with  the  task,  participants  will  first  complete  a  short  practice  block  to  get  them   
accustomed  to  the  task.  The  main  Stroop  task  will  consist  of  120  trials,  30  incongruent  and  90   
congruent.  On  each  trial,  the  participant  will  see  the  stimulus  (a  color  word  sized  100  ×  350  pixels)   
500  ms  after  the  onset  of  the  trial.  The  participant  will  then  have  1.5  s  to  make  a  response.  No   
feed-back  will  be  provided.  RGB  color  codes  (255,  0,  0),  (0,  255,  0),  (0,  0,  255)  will  be  used  for  red,   
green,  and  blue  respectively.  
 
 
 
After  performing  the  Stroop,  participants  will  be  randomly  assigned  to  one  of  four  reward-order  x   
trial-set  between-participants  conditions  (see  section  9)  by  the  card  sort  Inquisit  Web  program   
(cardsort.iqx)  and  informed  that  they  will  complete  another  computerized  task.  They  will  read  the  full   
instructions  for  a  modified  card-choice  version  of  the  task  used  by  Kool  et  al.  (2010).  Participants  will   
be  presented  with  a  picture  of  a  common  playing  card  of  one  of  two  suits:  Spades  (black)  and  Hearts   
(red).  Each  card  will  contain  a  red  or  black  number  in  the  center  (color  corresponding  to  the  suit  of   
the  card)  indicating  its  value;  the  cards  will  vary  from  2  to  9,  omitting  5.  The  number  stimulus  will  be   
presented  in  the  center,  the  top-left,  and  the  bottom-right  corners  of  a  white  “card”  in  a  40-point   
Times  New  Roman  font  in  either  red  or  black.  Upon  presentation  of  a  red  card  the  participant  will  use   
one  of  the  two  response  keys  ( f  or  j ,  respectively)  to  indicate  whether  the  card  is  smaller  or  larger   
than  5  (the  magnitude  task).  Upon  presentation  of  a  black  card,  the  participant  will  use  one  of  the   
two  response  keys  ( f  or  j ,  respectively)  to  indicate  whether  the  number  on  the  card  is  odd  or  even   
(the  parity  task).   
  
 
 
Participants  will  be  presented  with  the  stimulus  (card)  100  ms  after  the  onset  of  the  trial;  they  will   
have  3s  to  respond  and  will  be  given  feedback  on  the  correctness  of  their  response.  If  the  participant   
takes  too  long  to  answer,  the  trial  will  be  automatically  counted  as  a  miss  and  the  next  card  will  be   
shown.  Consistent  with  the  raw  data  files  from  the  original  study,  after  reading  all  of  the  instructions,   
participants  will  complete  a  practice  block  of  14  trials.   
  
 
 
Following  the  practice  block,  participants  will  complete  eight  items  from  an  Intrinsic  Motivation   
Inventory  adapted  from  the  activity  perception  questionnaire  used  Deci,  Egharari,  Patrick,  and   
Leone  (1994).  These  items  will  be  adapted  from  the  interest / enjoyment  subscale  and  will  be   
worded  to  ask  participants  to  forecast  their  experience  on  the  upcoming  task  (see  Intrinsic   
Motivation  Inventory.docx  and  cardsort.iqx).   Finally,  participants  will  receive  instructions  for  a   
performance-contingent  cash  bonus.   Based  on  their  randomized  condition  code,  they  will  either  be   
informed  that  they  will  receive  $.05  ( larger  reward )  or  $.01  ( smaller  reward )  for  each  correct  answer,   
and  will  complete  the  first  set  of  140  trials  of  the  main  task-switching  paradigm.   Following  this,   
participants  will  have  an  8-min  music  break,  featuring  a  selection  of  classical  pieces  by  Bach   
( rest_video.mp4 ),  and  then  complete  the  second  set  of  140  trials  of  the  task-switching  paradigm  in   
the  remaining  reward  condition.   Participants  will  receive  performance  feedback  after  each  trial  that   
is  specific  to  the  reward  condition  they  are  currently  completing.  
 
 
 
