15.
Stopping  rule  (optional)  
 
15.1.
If  your  data  collection  procedures  do  not  give  you  full  control  over  your  exact   
sample  size,  specify  how  you  will  decide  when  to  terminate  your  data  collection.   
  
15.2.
Example :  We  will  post  participant  sign-up  slots  by  week  on  the  preceding  Friday   
night,  with  20  spots  posted  per  week.  We  will  post  20  new  slots  each  week  if,  on   
that  Friday  night,  we  are  below  320  participants.   
  
15.3.
More  information :  You  may  specify  a  stopping  rule  based  on  p-values  only  in   
the  specific  case  of  sequential  analyses  with  pre-specified  checkpoints,  alphas   
levels,  and  stopping  rules.  Unacceptable  rationales  include  stopping  based  on   
p-values  if  checkpoints  and  stopping  rules  are  not  specified.  If  you  have  control   
over  your  sample  size,  then  including  a  stopping  rule  is  not  necessary,  though  it   
must  be  clear  in  this  question  or  a  previous  question  how  an  exact  sample  size  is   
attained.  
 
 
 
STOPPING  RULE:  
 
The  planned  sample  size  is  144 .  After  achieving  that  sample,  planned  analyses  will  be   
run.  If  a  significant  effect  is  found,  sampling  stops.  If  a  significant  effect  is  not  found,  a  second   
round  of  data  collection  will  collect  data  from  180  additional  participants,  for  a  pooled  sample  of   
324 .  Sampling  will  stop  after  the  second  round  of  data  collection  regardless  of  a  significant   
effect.  
 
______  
 
 
 
 

Variables  
 
 
 
In  this  section  you  can  describe  all  variables  (both  manipulated  and  measured  variables)  that   
will  later  be  used  in  your  confirmatory  analysis  plan.  In  your  analysis  plan,  you  will  have  the   
opportunity  to  describe  how  each  variable  will  be  used.  If  you  have  variables  which  you  are   
measuring  for  exploratory  analyses,  you  are  not  required  to  list  them,  though  you  are  permitted   
to  do  so.  
 
______  
 
 
 
16.
Manipulated  variables   
  
16.1.
Describe  all  variables  you  plan  to  manipulate  and  the  levels  or  treatment  arms  of   
each  variable.  This  is  not  applicable  to  any  observational  study.   
  
16.2.
Example:  We  manipulated  the  percentage  of  sugar  by  mass  added  to  brownies.   
The  four  levels  of  this  categorical  variable  are:  15%,  20%,  25%,  or  40%  cane   
sugar  by  mass.   
  
16.3.
More  information :  For  any  experimental  manipulation,  you  should  give  a  precise   
definition  of  each  manipulated  variable.  This  must  include  a  precise  description  of   
the  levels  at  which  each  variable  will  be  set,  or  a  specific  definition  for  each   
categorical  treatment.  For  example,  “loud  or  quiet,”  should  instead  give  either  a   
precise  decibel  level  or  a  means  of  recreating  each  level.  'Presence/absence'  or   
'positive/negative'  is  an  acceptable  description  if  the  variable  is  precisely   
described.  
 
 
 
MANIPULATED  VARIABLES:  
 
There  are  four  manipulated  variables.   The  first  will  be  whether  participants  will  perform  the   
same  or  a  different  task  in  consecutive  trials  on  the  task-switching  paradigm.   If  participants   
either  perform  two  consecutive  magnitude  judgments  when  viewing  a  red  card,  or  perform  two   
consecutive  parity  judgments  when  viewing  a  black  card,  their  responses  for  the  second   
judgment  will  be  scored  as  a  task-repeat  response.   If  participants  either  perform  a  parity   
judgment  when  viewing  a  black  card  immediately  following  a  magnitude  judgment  when  viewing   
a  red  card  or  a  magnitude  judgment  when  viewing  a  red  card  following  a  parity  judgment  when   
viewing  a  black  card,  their  responses  for  the  second  judgment  will  be  scored  as  a  task-switch   
response.   This  manipulation  is  within-participants  and  equal  numbers  of  both  types  of   
responses  will  be  required  in  each  of  14  blocks  of  the  task-switching  task,  as  detailed  above.  
 
 
 
The  second  manipulated  variable  will  be  whether  participants  complete  the  task-switch   
paradigm  with  the  incentive  of  either  $.05  for  each  correct  answer  ( larger  reward  condition)  or   
$.01  for  each  correct  answer  ( smaller  reward  condition).   This  manipulation  is  within-participants   
and  participants  will  complete  separate  full  sets  of  140  task-switch  trials  under  both  reward   
conditions,  as  detailed  above.  
 
 
 

The  third  and  fourth  manipulated  variables  will  be  whether  participants  complete  the   
larger-reward  set  of  task-switch  trials  first  and  the  smaller-reward  set  after  a  break,  and  with   
which  reward  condition  the  first  or  second  block-randomized  sequence  of  trials  will  be  paired   
(see  above).   This  2(reward)  x  2(order)  manipulation  is  between  participants  and  will  ensure  a   
fully  counterbalanced  design  for  the  reward-order  and  paired-sequence  manipulations.  
 
 
 
______  
 
 
 
 

17.
Measured  variables  (required)  
 
17.1.
Describe  each  variable  that  you  will  measure.  This  will  include  outcome   
measures,  as  well  as  any  predictors  or  covariates  that  you  will  measure.  You  do   
not  need  to  include  any  variables  that  you  plan  on  collecting  if  they  are  not  going   
to  be  included  in  the  confirmatory  analyses  of  this  study.  
 
17.2.
Example :  The  single  outcome  variable  will  be  the  perceived  tastiness  of  the   
single  brownie  each  participant  will  eat.  We  will  measure  this  by  asking   
participants  ‘How  much  did  you  enjoy  eating  the  brownie’  (on  a  scale  of  1-7,  1   
being  ‘not  at  all’,  7  being  ‘a  great  deal’)  and  ‘How  good  did  the  brownie  taste’  (on   
a  scale  of  1-7,  1  being  ‘very  bad’,  7  being  ‘very  good’).   
  
17.3.
More  information :  Observational  studies  and  meta-analyses  will  include  only   
measured  variables.  As  with  the  previous  questions,  the  answers  here  must  be   
precise.  For  example,  'intelligence,'  'accuracy,'  'aggression,'  and  'color'  are  too   
vague.  Acceptable  alternatives  could  be  'IQ  as  measured  by  Wechsler  Adult   
Intelligence  Scale'  'percent  correct,'  'number  of  threat  displays,'  and  'percent   
reflectance  at  400  nm.'  
 
 
 
MEASURED  VARIABLES:  
 
The  first  measured  independent  variable  will  be  participants’  executive  function,  as  assessed  by   
their  performance  on  the  Stroop  task.   Executive  function  will  be  calculated  as  the  difference   
between  standardized  RTs  on  incongruent  and  congruent  trials.   The  second  measured   
independent  variable  will  be  participants’  Need  for  Cognition,  as  assessed  by  their  responses  on   
the  18-item  scale  created  by  Cacioppo,  Petty,  and  Kao  (1984;  see  ncogscale.pdf).   The  third   
measured  independent  variable  will  be  participants’  scores  on  the  BIS/BAS  inventory  by  Carver   
&  White  (1994;  see  BISBAS.pdf).   The  fourth  measured  independent  variable  will  be   
participants’  anticipated  intrinsic  motivation  for  the  task-switching  task,  as  assessed  by  the   
seven-item  interest / enjoyment  subscale  on  the  activity  perception  questionnaire  created  by   
Deci,  Egharari,  Patrick,  and  Leone  (1994;  see  IMI.pdf),  with  the  items  reworded  to  be  in  the   
future  tense  concerning  the  upcoming  activity.  
 
 
 
The  first  measured  dependent  variable  will  be  participants’  reaction  times  (RTs)  on  each  trial  of   
the  task-switching  paradigm.   The  second  measured  dependent  variable  will  be  whether  or  not   
participants  responded  correctly  on  each  trial  of  the  task-switching  paradigm.   An  additional   
covariate  that  will  be  measured  for  inclusion  in  the  primary  analyses  will  be  the  block  number  of   
the  trials  of  the  task-switch  paradigm.  
 
______  
 
 
 
 

18.
Indices   
  
18.1.
If  any  measurements  are  going  to  be  combined  into  an  index  (or  even  a  mean),   
what  measures  will  you  use  and  how  will  they  be  combined?  Include  either  a   
formula  or  a  precise  description  of  your  method.  If  your  are  using  a  more   
complicated  statistical  method  to  combine  measures  (e.g.  a  factor  analysis),  you   
can  note  that  here  but  describe  the  exact  method  in  the  analysis  plan  section.  
 
18.2.
Example :  We  will  take  the  mean  of  the  two  questions  above  to  create  a  single   
measure  of  ‘brownie  enjoyment.’   
  
18.3.
More  information :  If  you  are  using  multiple  pieces  of  data  to  construct  a  single   
variable,  how  will  this  occur?  Both  the  data  that  are  included  and  the  formula  or   
weights  for  each  measure  must  be  specified.  Standard  summary  statistics,  such   
as  “means”  do  not  require  a  formula,  though  more  complicated  indices  require   
either  the  exact  formula  or,  if  it  is  an  established  index  in  the  field,  the  index  must   
be  unambiguously  defined.  For  example,  “biodiversity  index”  is  too  broad,   
whereas  “Shannon’s  biodiversity  index”  is  appropriate.  
 
 
 
INDICES:  
 
The  index  of  each  participant’s  executive  function  score  as  measured  by  the  Stroop  Task  will  be   
calculated  as  the  difference  between  standardized  mean  RTs  on  the  incongruent  and   
standardized  mean  RTs  congruent  trials.   The  indices  of  Need  for  Cognition,  BIS/BAS,  and   
anticipated  intrinsic  motivation  will  be  calculated  by  summing  participants’  responses  to  the   
relevant  items,  reverse-scored  where  appropriate,  as  detailed  in  the  documents  describing  each 
questionnaire.   Separate  mean  accuracy  and  mean  RT  indices  will  be  calculated  for   
participants’  responses  on  task-repeat  versus  task-switch  trials  in  each  block  of  both  sets  of   
trials  on  the  task-switch  paradigm.   A  block  number  index  will  also  be  created  for  the  task-switch   
paradigm  by  consecutively  numbering  each  set  of  14  trials  on  this  task  (see  the  Randomization   
section  for  further  details).  
 
 
 
 
 
______  
 
 
 
 

Analysis  Plan  
 
 
 
You  may  describe  one  or  more  confirmatory  analysis  in  this  preregistration.  Please  remember   
that  all  analyses  specified  below  must  be  reported  in  the  final  article,  and  any  additional   
analyses  must  be  noted  as  exploratory  or  hypothesis  generating.  
 
 
 
A  confirmatory  analysis  plan  must  state  up  front  which  variables  are  predictors  (independent)   
and  which  are  the  outcomes  (dependent),  otherwise  it  is  an  exploratory  analysis.  You  are   
allowed  to  describe  any  exploratory  work  here,  but  a  clear  confirmatory  analysis  is  required.   
  
  ______  
 
 
 
19.
Statistical  models  (required)  
 
19.1.
What  statistical  model  will  you  use  to  test  each  hypothesis?  Please  include  the   
type  of  model  (e.g.  ANOVA,  multiple  regression,  SEM,  etc)  and  the  specification   
of  the  model  (this  includes  each  variable  that  will  be  included  as  predictors,   
outcomes,  or  covariates).  Please  specify  any  interactions,  subgroup  analyses,   
pairwise  or  complex  contrasts,  or  follow-up  tests  from  omnibus  tests.  If  you  plan   
on  using  any  positive  controls,  negative  controls,  or  manipulation  checks  you   
may  mention  that  here.  Remember  that  any  test  not  included  here  must  be  noted   
as  an  exploratory  test  in  your  final  article.   
  
19.2.
Example :   We  will  use  a  one-way  between  subjects  ANOVA  to  analyze  our   
results.  The  manipulated,  categorical  independent  variable  is  'sugar'  whereas  the   
dependent  variable  is  our  taste  index.   
  
19.3.
More  information :  This  is  perhaps  the  most  important  and  most  complicated   
question  within  the  preregistration.  As  with  all  of  the  other  questions,  the  key  is  to   
provide  a  specific  recipe  for  analyzing  the  collected  data.  Ask  yourself:  is  enough   
detail  provided  to  run  the  same  analysis  again  with  the  information  provided  by   
the  user?  Be  aware  for  instances  where  the  statistical  models  appear  specific,   
but  actually  leave  openings  for  the  precise  test.  See  the  following  examples:   
  
19.3.1.1.
If  someone  specifies  a  2x3  ANOVA  with  both  factors  within   
subjects,  there  is  still  flexibility  with  the  various  types  of  ANOVAs   
that  could  be  run.  Either  a  repeated  measures  ANOVA   
(RMANOVA)  or  a  multivariate  ANOVA  (MANOVA)  could  be  used   
for  that  design,  which  are  two  different  tests.   
  
19.3.1.2.
If  you  are  going  to  perform  a  sequential  analysis  and  check  after   
50,  100,  and  150  samples,  you  must  also  specify  the  p-values   
you’ll  test  against  at  those  three  points.  
 
 
 
STATISTICAL  MODELS:  
 
The  primary  dependent  variables  of  mean  accuracy  and  RT  on  the  task-switch  task  will  be   
analyzed  using  multi-level  regression  models  specified  with  the  lme4  package  
 

(Pinheiro  &  Bates,  2000)  for  the  R  programming  language.   The  lmerTest  package   
( Kuznetsova,  Brockhoff,  &  Christensen,  2017),  which  uses  the  Satterthwaite’s  method  to   
calculate  degrees  of  freedom,  will  be  used  to  generate  p  values.   For  the  primary  replication   
analyses,  the  within-participants  reward  ( rewardlevel ;  -1  =  smaller  reward,  1  =  larger  reward)   
and  trial  type  ( trial ;  -1  =  task-repeat,  1  =  task-switch)  conditions  will  be  contrast  coded  and  the   
individual  difference  moderator  of  Need  for  Cognition  ( NFC )  will  be  entered  as  a  continuous   
variable.   A  continuous  covariate  that  indexes  10  separate  blocks  of  14  trials  in  the   
task-switching  paradigm  will  also  be  contrast-coded  ( blocknumber ;  -5,  -4,  -3,  -2,  -1,  1,  2,  3,  4,  5).   
The  analysis  will  have  a  two-level  structure  with  reward  and  trial  manipulated,  and  block  number   
measured,  at  Level  1  and  with  individual  differences  in  Need  for  Cognition  measured  at  Level  2.  
 
 
 
The  primary  replication  analysis  examining  the  three-way  interaction  of  Need  for  Cognition  with   
  
reaction  times  on  the  task-switching  paradigm  will  first  remove  all  incorrect  RT  scores  and  then   
log-transform  this  variable  as  specified  in  the  original  paper  (see  below).   The  transformed   
scores  will  then  be  analyzed  with  a  regression  model  specified  by  the  following  code:  
 
 
 
●
lmer(logRT  ~  NFC  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  (1|SubjectID))  
 
 
 
SubjectID  will  represent  the  numeric  code  assigned  to  each  individual  participant.   If  a 
significant  ( p  <  .05)  three-way  interaction  is  found,  follow-up  analyses  will  then  be  conducted  to   
examine  the  trial  x  rewardlevel  interactions  for  participants  high  versus  low  in  the  Need  for   
Cognition  by  creating  new  NFC  indices  centered  at  +1SD  ( HiNFC )  and  -1SD  ( LoNFC)  from  the   
sample  mean.   These  regression  models  will  be  specified  by  the  following  code:  
 
 
 
●
lmer(logRT  ~  HiNFC  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  (1|SubjectID))  
 
●
lmer(logRT  ~  LoNFC  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  (1|SubjectID))  
 
 
 
Several  additional  analyses  will  repeat  other  analyses  featured  in  the  original  paper.  The   
association  of  Need  for  Cognition  with  accuracy  scores  on  the  task-switching  task  (coded  0  =   
incorrect,  1  =  correct)  will  be  examined  with  a  binary  logistic  regression  model  specified  by  the   
following  code:  
 
 
 
●
glmer(accuracy  ~  NFC  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  (1|SubjectID),   
family=”binomial”)  
 
 
 
If  a  significant  ( p  <  .05)  three-way  interaction  is  found,  follow-up  analyses  will  then  be  conducted   
to  examine  the  trial  x  rewardlevel  interactions  for  participants  high  versus  low  in  the  Need  for   
Cognition  with  the  following  code:  
 
 
 
●
glmer(accuracy  ~  HiNFC  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  (1|SubjectID),   
family=”binomial”)  
 
●
glmer(accuracy  ~Lo  NFC  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  (1|SubjectID),   
family=”binomial”)  
 

 
 
 
 
Analyses  examining  the  association  of  executive  function  with  accuracy  and  reaction  time  to  test   
Hypothesis  1  will  follow  the  exact  same  procedures  as  above,  replacing  the  NFC  variable  with   
the  executive  function  index  calculated  from  the  Stroop  task  ( Stroopindex ;  see  details  above).   
  
 
 
●
lmer(logRT  ~  Stroopindex  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  (1|SubjectID))  
 
●
glmer(accuracy  ~  Stroopindex  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  (1|SubjectID),   
family=”binomial”)  
 
 
 
If  a  significant  ( p  <  .05)  three-way  interactions  are  found,  follow-up  analyses  will  then  be   
conducted  to  examine  the  trial  x  rewardlevel  interactions  for  participants  high  versus  low  in   
executive  function  by  creating  new  indices  centered  at  +1SD  ( HiStroopindex )  and  -1SD   
( LoStroopindex)  from  the  sample  mean.   These  regression  models  will  be  specified  by  the   
following  code:  
 
 
 
●
lmer(logRT  ~  HiStroopindex  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  (1|SubjectID))  
 
●
lmer(logRT  ~  LoStroopindex  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  (1|SubjectID))  
 
●
glmer(accuracy  ~  HiStroopindex  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  (1|SubjectID),   
family=”binomial”)  
 
●
glmer(accuracy  ~  LoStroopindex  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  (1|SubjectID),   
family=”binomial”)  
 
 
 
The  original  paper  featured  analyses  that  repeated  those  above  controlling  for  reward  sensitivity   
as  measured  by  the  BAS  index  as  an  additional  covariate.   However,  these  reported  analyses   
did  not  control  for  interactions  between  BAS  and  the  within-participants  manipulations  (see   
Yzerbyt,  Muller,  &  Judd,  2004).   To  improve  these  covariate  analyses,  the  present  study  will  add   
the  additional  interaction  terms  and  will  be  conducted  with  regression  models  specified  by  the   
following  code:  
 
 
 
●
lmer(logRT  ~  NFC  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  BAS  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +   
(1|SubjectID))  
 
●
glmer(accuracy  ~  NFC  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  BAS  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +   
(1|SubjectID),  family=”binomial”)  
 
●
lmer(logRT  ~  Stroopindex  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  BAS  *  trial  *  rewardlevel   
+  (1|SubjectID))  
 
●
glmer(accuracy  ~  Stroopindex  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  BAS  *  trial  *   
rewardlevel  +  (1|SubjectID),  family=”binomial”)  
 
 
 
To  test  Hypothesis  2,  the  primary  regression  analyses  will  be  repeated  replacing  the  Need  for   
Cognition  index  with  the  anticipated  intrinsic  motivation  index  ( IMI )  as  a  moderator.   These   
models  will  be  specified  by  the  following  code:  
 
 
 

●
lmer(logRT  ~  IMI  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  (1|SubjectID))  
 
●
glmer(accuracy  ~  IMI  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  (1|SubjectID),   
family=”binomial”)  
 
 
 
If  a  significant  ( p  <  .05)  three-way  interactions  are  found,  follow-up  analyses  will  then  be   
conducted  to  examine  the  trial  x  rewardlevel  interactions  for  participants  high  versus  low  in   
anticipated  intrinsic  motivation  by  creating  new  indices  centered  at  +1SD  ( HiIMI )  and  -1SD   
( LoIMI)  from  the  sample  mean.   These  regression  models  will  be  specified  by  the  following   
code:  
 
●
lmer(logRT  ~  HiIMI  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber   +  (1|SubjectID))  
 
●
lmer(logRT  ~  LoIMI  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  (1|SubjectID))  
 
●
glmer(accuracy  ~  HiIMI  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  (1|SubjectID),   
family=”binomial”)  
 
●
glmer(accuracy  ~  LoIMI  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  (1|SubjectID),   
family=”binomial”)  
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
______  
 
 
 
 

20.
Transformations  
 
20.1.
If  you  plan  on  transforming,  centering,  recoding  the  data,  or  will  require  a  coding   
scheme  for  categorical  variables,  please  describe  that  process.  
 
20.2.
Example :  The  “Effect  of  sugar  on  brownie  tastiness”  does  not  require  any   
additional  transformations.  However,  if  it  were  using  a  regression  analysis  and   
each  level  of  sweet  had  been  categorically  described  (e.g.  not  sweet,  somewhat   
sweet,  sweet,  and  very  sweet),  ‘sweet’  could  be  dummy  coded  with  ‘not  sweet’   
as  the  reference  category.   
  
20.3.
More  information :  If  any  categorical  predictors  are  included  in  a  regression,   
indicate  how  those  variables  will  be  coded  (e.g.  dummy  coding,  summation   
coding,  etc.)  and  what  the  reference  category  will  be.  
 
 
 
TRANSFORMATIONS:  
 
As  in  the  original  paper,  RT  analyses  will  only  be  performed  on  correct  answers,  and  RTs  for   
incorrect  answers  will  be  dropped  from  all  analyses.   The  remaining  RTs  will  be  transformed  with   
a  natural  log  before  analyses  are  conducted  (see  Data_cleaning_syntax.docx).  
 
 
 
All  categorical  variables  representing  experimental  conditions  will  be  coded  in  the  manner   
described  in  the  previous  section.   All  continuous  moderator  variables  will  be  standardized   
before  being  entered  into  the  regression  models  (see  Data_cleaning_syntax.docx).  
 
______  
 
 
 
 

21.
Inference  criteria  (optional)  
 
21.1.
What  criteria  will  you  use  to  make  inferences?  Please  describe  the  information   
youÍll  use  (e.g.  p-values,  bayes  factors,  specific  model  fit  indices),  as  well  as   
cut-off  criterion,  where  appropriate.  Will  you  be  using  one  or  two  tailed  tests  for   
each  of  your  analyses?  If  you  are  comparing  multiple  conditions  or  testing   
multiple  hypotheses,  will  you  account  for  this?  
 
21.2.
Example :  We  will  use  the  standard  p<.05  criteria  for  determining  if  the  ANOVA   
and  the  post  hoc  test  suggest  that  the  results  are  significantly  different  from  those   
expected  if  the  null  hypothesis  were  correct.  The  post-hoc  Tukey-Kramer  test   
adjusts  for  multiple  comparisons.   
  
21.3.
More  information:  P-values,  confidence  intervals,  and  effect  sizes  are  standard   
means  for  making  an  inference,  and  any  level  is  acceptable,  though  some  criteria   
must  be  specified  in  this  or  previous  fields.  Bayesian  analyses  should  specify  a 
Bayes  factor  or  a  credible  interval.  If  you  are  selecting  models,  then  how  will  you   
determine  the  relative  quality  of  each?  In  regards  to  multiple  comparisons,  this  is   
a  question  with  few  “wrong”  answers.  In  other  words,  transparency  is  more   
important  than  any  specific  method  of  controlling  the  false  discovery  rate  or  false   
error  rate.  One  may  state  an  intention  to  report  all  tests  conducted  or  one  may   
conduct  a  specific  correction  procedure;  either  strategy  is  acceptable.  
 
 
 
INFERENCE  CRITERIA:  
 
Criteria  for  a  successful  replication  attempt  for  the  SCORE  project  is  a  statistically   
significant  effect  (alpha  =  .05,  two  tailed)  in  the  same  pattern  as  the  original  study.  For  this   
replication  attempt,  this  criteria  is  met  for  the  focal  SCORE  test  (H*)  by  a  significant  three-way   
interaction  of  trial-type,  reward  amount,  and  Need  for  Cognition,  such  that  larger  rewards  lead  to   
smaller  differences  in  reaction  times  between  task-switch  and  task-repeat  trials  as  compared  to   
smaller  rewards  for  low-NFC  individuals,  but  this  effect  does  not  occur  for  high-NFC  individuals.  
 
 
 
 
 
______  
 
 
 
 

22.
Data  exclusion   
  
22.1.
How  will  you  determine  what  data  or  samples,  if  any,  to  exclude  from  your   
analyses?  How  will  outliers  be  handled?  Will  you  use  any  awareness  check? 
22.2.
Example :  No  checks  will  be  performed  to  determine  eligibility  for  inclusion   
besides  verification  that  each  subject  answered  each  of  the  three  tastiness   
indices.  Outliers  will  be  included  in  the  analysis.   
  
22.3.
More  information :  Any  rule  for  excluding  a  particular  set  of  data  is  acceptable.   
One  may  describe  rules  for  excluding  a  participant  or  for  identifying  outlier  data.  
 
 
 
DATA  EXCLUSIONS:  
 
 
 
Consistent  with  the  original  paper,  participants  who  score  lower  than  80%  accuracy  on  the   
Stroop  task  or  the  task-switching  paradigm  or  who  do  not  respond  within  the  maximum  allotted   
time  for  15  or  more  trials  in  either  task  will  not  be  included  in  any  analyses.   Participants  who  fail   
either  one  of  the  attention-check  items  embedded  in  the  Need  for  Cognition  and  BIS/BAS   
questionnaires  by  not  selecting  the  specified  option  will  also  be  excluded.   All  other  participants   
with  complete  responses  on  all  tasks  and  the  Need  for  Cognition  questionnaire  will  be  included   
in  the  analyses.   
  
______  
 
 
 
 

23.
Missing  data   
  
23.1.
How  will  you  deal  with  incomplete  or  missing  data?  
 
23.2.
Example :  If  a  subject  does  not  complete  any  of  the  three  indices  of  tastiness,   
that  subject  will  not  be  included  in  the  analysis.  
 
23.3.
More  information :  Any  relevant  explanation  is  acceptable.  As  a  final  reminder,   
remember  that  the  final  analysis  must  follow  the  specified  plan,  and  deviations   
must  be  either  strongly  justified  or  included  as  a  separate,  exploratory  analysis.  
 
 
 
MISSING  DATA:  
 
Consistent  with  the  original  paper,  participants  who  do  not  complete  all  of  the  items  on  the  Need   
for  Cognition  questionnaire  will  not  be  included  in  any  analyses.   Participants  who  do  not   
complete  all  of  the  items  on  the  BIS/BAS  or  anticipated  intrinsic  motivation  questionnaires  will   
not  be  included  in  the  analyses  involving  these  moderators.  
 
 
 
Also  consistent  with  the  original  paper,  participants  who  miss  15  or  more  response  deadlines   
during  the  Stoop  task  or  during  either  of  the  two  sets  of  trials  on  task-switching  paradigm  will  not   
be  included  in  any  analyses.   
  
