24.
Exploratory  analysis  (optional)  
 
24.1.
If  you  plan  to  explore  your  data  set  to  look  for  unexpected  differences  or   
relationships,  you  may  describe  those  tests  here.  An  exploratory  test  is  any  test   
where  a  prediction  is  not  made  up  front,  or  there  are  multiple  possible  tests  that   
you  are  going  to  use.  A  statistically  significant  finding  in  an  exploratory  test  is  a   
great  way  to  form  a  new  confirmatory  hypothesis,  which  could  be  registered  at  a   
later  time.   
  
24.2.
Example :  We  expect  that  certain  demographic  traits  may  be  related  to  taste   
preferences.  Therefore,  we  will  look  for  relationships  between  demographic   
variables  (age,  gender,  income,  and  marital  status)  and  the  primary  outcome   
measures  of  taste  preferences.  
 
 
 
EXPLORATORY  ANALYSIS:  
 
 
 
If  significant  three-way  interactions  are  found  for  either  accuracy  or  reactions  times  in  both  the   
Need  for  Cognition  analyses  and  the  anticipated  intrinsic  motivation  analyses  described  above,   
follow-up  analyses  will  be  conducted  in  which  both  effects  are  examined  controlling  for  the   
other:  
 
●
lmer(logRT  ~  NFC  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  IMI  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +   
(1|SubjectID))  
 
●
glmer(accuracy  ~  NFC  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  IMI  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +   
(1|SubjectID),  family=”binomial”)  
 
 
 
These  analyses  will  explore  whether  either  one  of  these  two  individual  difference  measures  is  a   
better  measure  of  the  proposed  intrinsic  motivation  effect  in  the  original  paper.   It  is  possible  that   
specifically  asking  people  about  their  anticipated  interest  in  the  upcoming  task  better  captures   
this  construct  than  the  more  general  measure  of  Need  for  Cognition.  
 
 
 
If  a  significant  ( p  <  .05)  three-way  interactions  are  found  for  either  moderator,  follow-up  analyses   
will  then  be  conducted  to  examine  the  trial  x  rewardlevel  interactions  for  participants  scoring   
high  versus  low  on  that  variable  using  the  indices  describe  above.   These  regression  models  will   
be  specified  by  the  following  code:  
 
 
 
●
lmer(logRT  ~  [HiIMI  or  HiNFC]  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber   +  (1|SubjectID))  
 
●
lmer(logRT  ~  [LoIMI  o  LoNFC]  *  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  (1|SubjectID))  
 
●
glmer(accuracy  ~  [HiIMI  or  HiNFC]*  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  (1|SubjectID),   
family=”binomial”)  
 
●
glmer(accuracy  ~  [LoIMI  o  LoNFC]*  trial  *  rewardlevel  +  blocknumber  +  (1|SubjectID),   
family=”binomial”)  
 
 
 
